Salesforce DX project.Use force-app/main/default only.Never create src,metadata,mdapi.

Paths:
classes:force-app/main/default/classes
lwc:force-app/main/default/lwc
triggers:force-app/main/default/triggers
objects:force-app/main/default/objects
customMetadata:force-app/main/default/customMetadata
labels:force-app/main/default/labels

All metadata must include meta.xml pair.

Examples:
MyClass.cls + MyClass.cls-meta.xml
AccountTrigger.trigger + AccountTrigger.trigger-meta.xml
LWC must contain js,html,js-meta.xml

Target org alias:JUNHO-DEV.Verify using sf config get target-org.

Apex default:public with sharing class.

Security checks mandatory:
WITH USER_MODE
or Security.stripInaccessible()

Never ignore CRUD/FLS.

Strictly forbid:
SOQL in loops
DML in loops
hardcoded credentials

All logic must be bulk safe.

Trigger rules:
Triggers must stay thin.
No business logic in triggers.
Use architecture:
Trigger → Handler → Service

Example:
AccountTrigger
AccountTriggerHandler
AccountService

Query rules:
Prefer WHERE clause.
Avoid full table scans.
Use LIMIT when possible.

Governor limits must always be considered.

LWC rules:
Component must contain:
component.js
component.html
component.js-meta.xml

Validate decorators:
@api
@wire
@track

Avoid unnecessary @track.

Test requirements:
Minimum 75% coverage.
Create test classes for new logic.
Use @isTest.
Use Test.startTest() and Test.stopTest().
Avoid SeeAllData=true.

Git commit prefixes:
[Sync]
[Feat]
[Fix]
[Refactor]

Example:
[Feat] Account validation service

Security guard:
Never hardcode:
OrgId
APIKeys
Tokens
Credentials

Use instead:
Custom Metadata
Named Credentials
Custom Settings

MCP usage:
Salesforce MCP only for schema inspection and metadata lookup.
Do not auto deploy.

Git MCP must run from repository root.

Always run git diff before suggesting commits.

Apex syntax guard:
Inner classes cannot contain static members.
Move static logic to top-level utility classes.

Utility usage rules:
Always reuse existing `Util*` classes instead of creating new private helper methods.
- For Dates: `UtilDate`, `UtilDatetime`
- For Collections: `UtilList`, `UtilMap`
- For Schema/SObjects: `UtilSchema`, `UtilSObject`
- For Queries/DML: `UtilQuery`, `UtilWithoutSharing`

Extension & Pattern rules:
When creating new Security features, implement `ISecurityAction` or extend `SecurityBaseAction`.
When handling inbound requests, use `IInboundAction` and route through `SecurityActionInboundHandler`.
Use Factory patterns (`SecurityActionFactory`, `InterfaceFactory`) for instantiating logic.

Logging & Error handling:
Do not rely only on System.debug().
For security or system-level processes, use the existing logging framework (e.g., `SecuritySoarTrace`).

Testing conventions:
Test classes must be named `{ClassName}_test`. (Do not use `Test{ClassName}` or `{ClassName}Test`)
All test methods must use `@isTest`.
Mocking and TestDataFactory usage is preferred over inline data creation if available.

LWC naming conventions:
Component folder names must be strict `camelCase` (e.g., `myCustomComponent`).
Avoid using `test_` or arbitrary prefixes unless it is a temporary scratch file.

General architecture rules:
Prefer service layer design.
Controllers and triggers should only orchestrate.
Business logic must live in service classes.

## 🌐 Encoding & Annotation Rules (Critical)
- **UTF-8 (No BOM) Mandatory:** All source files (.cls, .trigger, .js, .html) MUST be saved in UTF-8 encoding.
- **Korean Comments Handling:** - When writing Korean comments, ensure the IDE encoding is set to UTF-8 to prevent "濡쒓렇" style corruption.
  - For critical logic explanations, prefer **English comments** to ensure maximum compatibility across different IDEs (IntelliJ, VS Code, Salesforce Console).
  - Use Javadoc style (`/** ... */`) for class and method headers to maintain professional documentation.
- **No Hardcoded Strings:** Use `Custom Labels` for UI/Log strings, but comments can remain in Korean/English if encoding is strictly UTF-8.

Workflow output after coding:
[NextStep]
1.Verify metadata and meta.xml under force-app
2.Deploy via IntelliJ or sf CLI
3.Verify in org
4.Commit and push